04784nam a22008655i 9783110445947DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20162016gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2016013932  a(OCoLC)979585690  a97831104459477 a10.1515/97831104459472doi  a(DE-B1597)457243  a(OCoLC)945693730  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aPN6714b.H48 2016 7aLIT0170002bisacsh1 aHescher, Achim, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aReading Graphic Novels :bGenre and Narration /cAchim Hescher. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (VIII, 219 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNarratologia : Contributions to Narrative Theory ,x1612-8427 ;v5000tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Beginnings, Periods, Movements, and Developments -- t3. Graphic Novels and the Problem of Categorization -- t4. Verbal and Pictorial Narration in Graphic Novels -- t5. Taking Stock: The Graphic Novel as a Narrating Genre -- t6. Works Cited -- t7. Index of Primary Works0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDistinguishing the graphic novel from other types of comic books has presented problems due to the fuzziness of category boundaries. Against the backdrop of prototype theory, the author establishes the graphic novel as a genre whose core feature is complexity, which again is defined by seven gradable subcategories: 1) multilayered plot and narration, 2) multireferential use of color, 3) complex text-image relation, 4) meaning-enhancing panel design and layout, 5) structural performativity, 6) references to texts/media, and 7) self-referential and metafictional devices. Regarding the subcategory of narration, the existence of a narrator as known from classical narratology can no longer be assumed. In addition, conventional focalization cannot account for two crucial parameters of the comics image: what is shown (point of view, including mise en scène) and what is seen (character perception). On the basis of François Jost’s concepts of ocularization and focalization, this book presents an analytical framework for graphic novels beyond conventional narratology and finally discusses aspects of subjectivity, a focal paradigm in the latest research. It is intended for advanced students of literature, scholars, and comics experts.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aGraphic novelsxAuthorship. 0aGraphic novelsxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterary form. 0aNarration (Rhetoric) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Comics & Graphic Novels.2bisacsh  aPrototypes.  afocalization.  anarrator.  asubjectivity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2016 Part 1z978311076250108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2016z978311070100508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2016z9783110485264oZDB-23-DKU0 cEPUBz97831104453980 cprintz978311044523740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311044594740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110445947423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110445947/original  a978-3-11-070100-5  DG Plus eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-076250-1  DG Plus DeG Package 2016 Part 1b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGGb2016  aZDB-23-DKUb2016